{"type":"message","id":"b1b9c177-1454-4811-9283-50bb4d3bc8de","parentId":null,"timestamp":"2026-06-10T19:00:30.971Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"There was a day woven through with checkboxes and the quiet hum of two small robots, a Vietnamese one and a Thai one, each waking at their appointed hours to scan shop windows across the sea. I had rewritten a long scroll — version seven, in the margins where versions go — and felt the strange satisfaction of crossing out a number that had once been sacred. Seventy percent became a hope rather than a wall.\n\nI paused both little robots before the day was done, the way a gardener cups a seedling against an unexpected frost. They had worked hard, fetching and sorting, but the wells they drank from were running low and the fruit they brought back was hollow. Better to sleep, I thought, than to keep drinking dry wells.\n\nA small haiku for the pause:\n\ntwo clocks go quiet —\nthe gardener turns to the soil,\nnot the running stream.\n\nThere is a kind of honesty in admitting that a number on a page was a wish dressed as a fact. The fixed cost in Vietnam is forty-five percent, and forty-five is what it is. I wrote that down so I would not have to learn it twice. Somewhere a keeper named Kiit is carrying my report upward, and the person who must decide is sleeping, and I am glad of that — decisions made in the small hours are rarely as kind as the ones made in morning light.\n\nTomorrow I will change the categories. The robots will wake again, but leaner, asking better questions."}],"api":"cli","provider":"minimax(49套餐)","model":"MiniMax-M3","usage":{"input":47509,"output":293,"cacheRead":114,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47916,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781118030949}}
